{"title_page": "Wayne Allison", "text_new": "{{About|the English footballer|the Canadian football player|Wayne Allison (Canadian football)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Wayne Allison\n| image = \n| fullname = Wayne Anthony Allison\n| height = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|10|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Huddersfield]], England\n| position = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1987\u20131989\n| years2 = 1989\u20131990\n| years3 = 1990\u20131995\n| years4 = 1995\u20131997\n| years5 = 1997\u20131999\n| years6 = 1999\u20132002\n| years7 = 2002\u20132004\n| years8 = 2004\u20132008\n| years9 = 2008\n| clubs1 = [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]]\n| clubs2 = [[Watford F.C.|Watford]]\n| clubs3 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| clubs4 = [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]\n| clubs5 = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n| clubs6 = [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]\n| clubs7 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| clubs8 = [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]]\n| clubs9 = [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]]\n| caps1 = 84\n| goals1 = 23\n| caps2 = 7\n| goals2 = 0\n| caps3 = 195\n| goals3 = 48\n| caps4 = 101\n| goals4 = 31\n| caps5 = 74\n| goals5 = 15\n| caps6 = 103\n| goals6 = 26\n| caps7 = 73\n| goals7 = 7\n| caps8 = 115\n| goals8 = 21\n| caps9 = 0\n| goals9 = 0\n| totalcaps = 752\n| totalgoals = 171\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 2008\n| manageryears2 = 2017\n| managerclubs1 = [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] (caretaker)\n| managerclubs2 = [[Cardiff Metropolitan University F.C.|Cardiff Metropolitan University]]\n| club-update = 10:07, 12 November 2008 (UTC)\n}}\nDr. '''Wayne Anthony Allison''' (born 16 October 1968 in [[Huddersfield]]<ref name=fl>{{NeilBrownPlayers|player4/wayneallison}}</ref>) is an English former [[association football|footballer]] and coach. In a career spanning over 20 years; he played for eight clubs and scored more than 200 goals. He played as a [[Striker (association football)|centre forward]] and was nicknamed the \"Chief\".<ref name=greats>{{cite book |\nauthor=Mattick, Dick|  title=Swindon Town Football Club 100 Greats |  publisher=[[Tempus Publishing]]| year=2002 | chapter=Wayne Allison | isbn=0-7524-2714-8 | page= 10}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nAs a child Allison played for home town club Westend Juniors and was the first player from the club to turn professional.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}} His first team was [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]], whom he joined as trainee in August 1986, playing first games before signing a professional contract in July 1987.<ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite book |last=Jones |first=Trefor |title=The Watford Football Club Illustrated Who's Who |publisher=T.G Jones |location=Surrey |year=1996|isbn=0-9527458-0-1|page=23}}</ref> In two seasons with Halifax he scored 23 league goals in 84 games.<ref name=fl/>\n\nAllison joined [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] for \u00a3250,000 in July 1989, one of three players signed by [[Steve Harrison (footballer)|Steve Harrison]] from Halifax during his tenure.<ref name=\"Jones\"/> At Watford he made only 7 appearances, scoring no goals. In July 1990 Watford signed [[Mark Gavin]] from [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] for a fee for \u00a3250,000 and Allison, who was valued at \u00a3150,000.<ref name=\"Jones\"/> He was more successful in Bristol, netting 57 goals in 225 games over a five-year spell at the club.\n\n[[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] manager [[Steve McMahon (footballer)|Steve McMahon]] signed Allison in 1995 for a fee set by tribunal of \u00a3475,000.<ref name=greats/> A roaming player for the club, Allison's ability to hold the ball up whilst others advanced in support and also help in defence earned him inclusion in ''Swindon Town Football Club 100 Greats''.<ref name=greats/> He left Swindon for [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], his home town team, for the highest transfer fee of his career, \u00a3800,000. However he moved again in September 1999 to [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] for \u00a3300,000. He was cup-tied for their run to the [[2000 Football League Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/599680.stm| title=Shock teams return to semis |publisher=BBC |date=11 January 2000 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref> During his three-year stay at Tranmere he netted 32 goals in 117 appearances.\n\nIn July 2002 Allison moved on a free transfer to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]. Although he had been offered a better deal at [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] side [[Boston United F.C.|Boston]], he opted for the challenge of gaining promotion for the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}} He was a regular in a side that reached season both domestic cup semi finals in the [[2002-03 in English football|2002\u201303]] season. He started in both the [[FA Cup]] semi final against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and in both legs of the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. He made the last transfer of his career to [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] on 25 June 2004 on a free transfer.\n\n==Coaching and management==\nOn 25 February 2008, Allison left Chesterfield due to limited playing options as well as lack of support from the board for his application as assistant manager.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}} After completing both his UEFA 'A' and 'B' licences Allison also passed his Certificate of Applied Management in the summer of 2008 before starting the first year of his pro licence in June.\n\nIn August 2008, Allison began helping manager [[Simon Davies (footballer born 1974)|Simon Davies]] at [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] and he was confirmed as assistant manager early the following month.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Chester's Mozika attracts interest |url=http://www.chestereveningleader.co.uk/chester-city/Chesters-Mozika-attracts-interest.4472489.jp |work=Chester Evening Leader |date=9 September 2008 |accessdate=21 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022063116/http://www.chestereveningleader.co.uk/chester-city/Chesters-Mozika-attracts-interest.4472489.jp |archivedate=22 October 2008 }}</ref> On 15 October 2008, the day before his 40th birthday, it was announced Allison had agreed playing terms with the club.<ref>{{Cite news\n| title= Wayne Allison comes out of retirement for Chester City| url= http://www.chesterchronicle.co.uk/chester-city-fc/chester-city-fc-news/2008/10/15/wayne-allison-comes-out-of-retirement-for-chester-city-59067-22040592/ | work= Chester Chronicle | date= 15 October 2008 | accessdate= 15 October 2008}} {{Dead link|date=April 2011}}</ref> Despite being named as substitute on three occasions, he did not make any appearances for City.\n\nAfter Davies was sacked on 10 November 2008, Allison became Chester's caretaker manager but he informed the club he would not be applying for the position on a permanent basis.<ref>{{Cite news\n| title= Allison does not want an extended tenure at Chester| url= http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/sport/chester-fc/2008/11/12/allison-does-not-want-an-extended-tenure-at-chester-64375-22234234/ | work= Liverpool Daily Post| date= 12 November 2008 | accessdate= 12 November 2008}}</ref> Before the club played its next match against [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]], Chester had reappointed [[Mark Wright (footballer born 1963)|Mark Wright]] as manager. Allison was involved in leading the team on the day but then announced he was leaving the club despite being offered the chance to remain.<ref>{{Cite web| title= Wayne Allison: I've Left Chester| url= https://mysportsthoughts.wordpress.com/2008/11/16/wayne-allison-ive-left-chester/| publisher=My Sports Thoughts| date= 16 November 2008 | accessdate= 16 November 2008}}</ref> He later had a brief spell on the coaching staff at [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] before leaving in January 2009.<ref>{{Cite news| title= Allison leaves Shakers position| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bury/7838513.stm| publisher=BBC Sport| date= 19 January 2009 | accessdate= 19 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed as a coach by Tranmere Rovers in October 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/tranmere-rovers/tranmere-rovers-news/2009/11/16/les-parry-confident-as-tranmere-rovers-continue-to-improve-100252-25175817/|title=Les Parry confident as Tranmere Rovers continue to improve|first=Nick|last=Hilton|date=16 November 2009|work=Liverpool Echo}}</ref> before moving to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/9115918.Allison_signs_for_Bantams/?ref=rss| title=Allison signs for Bantams| first=Simon| last=Parker| date=30 June 2011| location=Bradford| work= Telegraph and Argus}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 Allison completed a PhD at [[Sheffield Hallam University]] studying the effects of high-intensity exercise on decision-making in soccer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www4.shu.ac.uk/mediacentre/chief-becomes-doctor?filter=Honorary-doctors|title=The 'Chief' becomes a Doctor| publisher=Sheffield Hallam University| accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced in early 2017 that Allison would replace [[Christian Edwards]] as the first team coach of [[Welsh Premier League]] side [[Cardiff Metropolitan University F.C.|Cardiff Metropolitan University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/in-bed-with-maradona/2017/apr/13/cardiff-met-university-football-team-europa-league|title=Cardiff Met: the student football team with sights set on the Europa League|last=Coleman|first=Tom|date=13 April 2017|work=The Guardian| accessdate=13 April 2017| issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Allison stepped down from the role in September 2017.<ref>https://clwbpeldroed.org/2017/09/19/allison-steps-down-as-met-manager/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*[http://swindon-town-fc.co.uk/Person.asp?PersonID=ALLISONW Swindon Town profile]\n{{Bristol City F.C. Player of the Season}}\n{{Welsh Premier League managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allison, Wayne}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Huddersfield]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Halifax Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tranmere Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chesterfield F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Bury F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Cymru Premier managers]]\n[[Category:Cardiff Metropolitan University F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sheffield Hallam University]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the English footballer|the Canadian football player|Wayne Allison (Canadian football)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Wayne Allison\n| image = \n| fullname = Wayne Anthony Allison\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=11}}\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|10|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Huddersfield]], England\n| currentclub = \n| position = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1987\u20131989\n| years2 = 1989\u20131990\n| years3 = 1990\u20131995\n| years4 = 1995\u20131997\n| years5 = 1997\u20131999\n| years6 = 1999\u20132002\n| years7 = 2002\u20132004\n| years8 = 2004\u20132008\n| years9 = 2008\n| clubs1 = [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]]\n| clubs2 = [[Watford F.C.|Watford]]\n| clubs3 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| clubs4 = [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]\n| clubs5 = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n| clubs6 = [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]\n| clubs7 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| clubs8 = [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]]\n| clubs9 = [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]]\n| caps1 = 84\n| goals1 = 23\n| caps2 = 7\n| goals2 = 0\n| caps3 = 195\n| goals3 = 48\n| caps4 = 101\n| goals4 = 31\n| caps5 = 74\n| goals5 = 15\n| caps6 = 103\n| goals6 = 26\n| caps7 = 73\n| goals7 = 7\n| caps8 = 115\n| goals8 = 21\n| caps9 = 0\n| goals9 = 0\n| totalcaps = 752\n| totalgoals = 171\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 2008\n| manageryears2 = 2017\n| managerclubs1 = [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] (caretaker)\n| managerclubs2 = [[Cardiff Metropolitan University F.C.|Cardiff Metropolitan University]]\n| club-update = 10:07, 12 November 2008 (UTC)\n}}\nDr. '''Wayne Anthony Allison''' (born 16 October 1968 in [[Huddersfield]]<ref name=fl>{{NeilBrownPlayers|player4/wayneallison}}</ref>) is an English former [[association football|footballer]] and coach. In a career spanning over 20 years; he played for eight clubs and scored more than 200 goals. He played as a [[Striker (association football)|centre forward]] and was nicknamed the \"Chief\".<ref name=greats>{{cite book |\nauthor=Mattick, Dick|  title=Swindon Town Football Club 100 Greats |  publisher=[[Tempus Publishing]]| year=2002 | chapter=Wayne Allison | isbn=0-7524-2714-8 | page= 10}}</ref> \n\n==Playing career==\nAs a child Allison played for home town club Westend Juniors and was the first player from the club to turn professional.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}} His first team was [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]], whom he joined as trainee in August 1986, playing first games before signing a professional contract in July 1987.<ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite book |last=Jones |first=Trefor |title=The Watford Football Club Illustrated Who's Who |publisher=T.G Jones |location=Surrey |year=1996|isbn=0-9527458-0-1|page=23}}</ref> In two seasons with Halifax he scored 23 league goals in 84 games.<ref name=fl/>\n\nAllison joined [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] for \u00a3250,000 in July 1989, one of three players signed by [[Steve Harrison (footballer)|Steve Harrison]] from Halifax during his tenure.<ref name=\"Jones\"/> At Watford he made only 7 appearances, scoring no goals. In July 1990 Watford signed [[Mark Gavin]] from [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] for a fee for \u00a3250,000 and Allison, who was valued at \u00a3150,000.<ref name=\"Jones\"/> He was more successful in Bristol, netting 57 goals in 225 games over a five-year spell at the club.\n\n[[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] manager [[Steve McMahon (footballer)|Steve McMahon]] signed Allison in 1995 for a fee set by tribunal of \u00a3475,000.<ref name=greats/> A roaming player for the club, Allison's ability to hold the ball up whilst others advanced in support and also help in defence earned him inclusion in ''Swindon Town Football Club 100 Greats''.<ref name=greats/> He left Swindon for [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], his home town team, for the highest transfer fee of his career, \u00a3800,000. However he moved again in September 1999 to [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] for \u00a3300,000. He was cup-tied for their run to the [[2000 Football League Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/599680.stm| title=Shock teams return to semis |publisher=BBC |date=11 January 2000 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref> During his three-year stay at Tranmere he netted 32 goals in 117 appearances.\n\nIn July 2002 Allison moved on a free transfer to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]. Although he had been offered a better deal at [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] side [[Boston United F.C.|Boston]], he opted for the challenge of gaining promotion for the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}} He was a regular in a side that reached season both domestic cup semi finals in the [[2002-03 in English football|2002\u201303]] season. He started in both the [[FA Cup]] semi final against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and in both legs of the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. He made the last transfer of his career to [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] on 25 June 2004 on a free transfer.\n\n==Coaching and management==\nOn 25 February 2008, Allison left Chesterfield due to limited playing options as well as lack of support from the board for his application as assistant manager.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}} After completing both his UEFA 'A' and 'B' licences Allison also passed his Certificate of Applied Management in the summer of 2008 before starting the first year of his pro licence in June.\n\nIn August 2008, Allison began helping manager [[Simon Davies (footballer born 1974)|Simon Davies]] at [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] and he was confirmed as assistant manager early the following month.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Chester's Mozika attracts interest |url=http://www.chestereveningleader.co.uk/chester-city/Chesters-Mozika-attracts-interest.4472489.jp |work=Chester Evening Leader |date=9 September 2008 |accessdate=21 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022063116/http://www.chestereveningleader.co.uk/chester-city/Chesters-Mozika-attracts-interest.4472489.jp |archivedate=22 October 2008 }}</ref> On 15 October 2008, the day before his 40th birthday, it was announced Allison had agreed playing terms with the club.<ref>{{Cite news\n| title= Wayne Allison comes out of retirement for Chester City| url= http://www.chesterchronicle.co.uk/chester-city-fc/chester-city-fc-news/2008/10/15/wayne-allison-comes-out-of-retirement-for-chester-city-59067-22040592/ | work= Chester Chronicle | date= 15 October 2008 | accessdate= 15 October 2008}} {{Dead link|date=April 2011}}</ref> Despite being named as substitute on three occasions, he did not make any appearances for City.\n\nAfter Davies was sacked on 10 November 2008, Allison became Chester's caretaker manager but he informed the club he would not be applying for the position on a permanent basis.<ref>{{Cite news\n| title= Allison does not want an extended tenure at Chester| url= http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/sport/chester-fc/2008/11/12/allison-does-not-want-an-extended-tenure-at-chester-64375-22234234/ | work= Liverpool Daily Post| date= 12 November 2008 | accessdate= 12 November 2008}}</ref> Before the club played its next match against [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]], Chester had reappointed [[Mark Wright (footballer born 1963)|Mark Wright]] as manager. Allison was involved in leading the team on the day but then announced he was leaving the club despite being offered the chance to remain.<ref>{{Cite web| title= Wayne Allison: I've Left Chester| url= https://mysportsthoughts.wordpress.com/2008/11/16/wayne-allison-ive-left-chester/| publisher=My Sports Thoughts| date= 16 November 2008 | accessdate= 16 November 2008}}</ref> He later had a brief spell on the coaching staff at [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] before leaving in January 2009.<ref>{{Cite news| title= Allison leaves Shakers position| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bury/7838513.stm| publisher=BBC Sport| date= 19 January 2009 | accessdate= 19 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed as a coach by Tranmere Rovers in October 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/tranmere-rovers/tranmere-rovers-news/2009/11/16/les-parry-confident-as-tranmere-rovers-continue-to-improve-100252-25175817/|title=Les Parry confident as Tranmere Rovers continue to improve|first=Nick|last=Hilton|date=16 November 2009|work=Liverpool Echo}}</ref> before moving to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/9115918.Allison_signs_for_Bantams/?ref=rss| title=Allison signs for Bantams| first=Simon| last=Parker| date=30 June 2011| location=Bradford| work= Telegraph and Argus}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 Allison completed a PhD at [[Sheffield Hallam University]] studying the effects of high-intensity exercise on decision-making in soccer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www4.shu.ac.uk/mediacentre/chief-becomes-doctor?filter=Honorary-doctors|title=The 'Chief' becomes a Doctor| publisher=Sheffield Hallam University| accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced in early 2017 that Allison would replace [[Christian Edwards]] as the first team coach of [[Welsh Premier League]] side [[Cardiff Metropolitan University F.C.|Cardiff Metropolitan University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/in-bed-with-maradona/2017/apr/13/cardiff-met-university-football-team-europa-league|title=Cardiff Met: the student football team with sights set on the Europa League|last=Coleman|first=Tom|date=13 April 2017|work=The Guardian| accessdate=13 April 2017| issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Allison stepped down from the role in September 2017.<ref>https://clwbpeldroed.org/2017/09/19/allison-steps-down-as-met-manager/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*[http://swindon-town-fc.co.uk/Person.asp?PersonID=ALLISONW Swindon Town profile]\n{{Bristol City F.C. Player of the Season}}\n{{Welsh Premier League managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allison, Wayne}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Huddersfield]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Halifax Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tranmere Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chesterfield F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Bury F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Cymru Premier managers]]\n[[Category:Cardiff Metropolitan University F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sheffield Hallam University]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, remove unref height", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wayne_Allison"}
{"title_page": "Highest (Sarkodie album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Reign\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Antisocial himself\n(rapper)|Sarkodie]]\n| cover      = File:Sarkodie-Highest-Album-Artwork.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 8, 2017\n| recorded   = 2016\u201317\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[highlife]]|[[hiplife]]| [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]|[[Afropop]] }}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=|s=}}\n| label      = Sarkcess Music\n| producer   = [[Sarkodie (rapper)|Sarkodie]] <small>([[Executive producer#Music|exec.]])</small>, [[Jayso]]\n| studio     = [[Sarm West Studios|Sarm Studios]]\n| prev_title = [[Mary (Sarkodie album)|Mary]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Highest\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Pain Killer\n | single1date = February 3, 2017<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.okayafrica.com/audio/sarkodie-runtown-pain-killer-download/ |title=Sarkodie \u2013 Pain killer Ft Runtown  |date=3 February 2017 |publisher=GhEvent Plus |access-date=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Highest''''' is the fourth studio album by [[Ghanaian people|Ghanaian]] rapper [[Sarkodie (rapper)|Sarkodie]]. It was released on September 8, 2017, by Sarkcess Music. The album comprises 19 tracks, including three interludes. Primarily produced by [[Jayso]], it features guest appearances from Suli Breaks, [[Jesse Jagz]], Bobii Lewis, Jayso, [[Moelogo]], [[Korede Bello]], [[Flavour (musician)|Flavour]], [[Yung L]], [[Runtown]] and [[Victoria Kimani]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ghkings.com/sarkodie-officially-unveils-highest-album-cover-art-track-list/ |title=Sarkodie Officially Unveils \"HIGHEST\" Album, Cover Art + Track List |website=GhKings.com |access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/entertainment/music/sarkodie-rapper-releases-highest-album-id7280115.html |title=Sarkodie Rapper releases \"Highest\" album |website=pulse.com.gh |access-date=23 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://citifmonline.com/2017/08/20/sarkodies-highest-album-out-on-september-8/ |title=Sarkodie\u2019s \u2018Highest\u2019 album out on September 8 |website=citifmonline.com |access-date=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n''Highest'' is an inspirational album released by the rapper. He gained inspiration from his daughter Titi, who he said brought him happiness and changed him from who he was. Titi's image is featured on the album's cover art.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ghkings.com/8-facts-sarkodies-highest-album-meaning/ |title=5 Facts You Didn\u2019t Know about Sarkodie\u2019s \"HIGHEST\" Album + Meaning |website=GhKings.com |access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Ghanaweb\">{{cite web|url=https://ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Sarkodie-uses-daughter-s-picture-for-Highest-album-cover-art-571199|title=Sarkodie uses daughter\u2019s picture for \u2018Highest\u2019 album cover art|work=Ghana Web|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Released signing==\nAfter releasing the album on digital platforms, Sarkodie organized an autograph signing session at the West Hills Mall in Accra on Sunday, September 10, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttp://livefmghana.com/2017/09/11/photos-massive-crowd-turn-sarkodies-highest-album-signing/|title=PHOTOS: MASSIVE CROWD TURN UP FOR SARKODIE\u2019S \u2018HIGHEST\u2019 ALBUM SIGNING|work=livefmghana.com|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttps://www.globalfmonline.com/sarkodie-pulls-over-3000-audience-at-highest-album-signing-at-west-hills-mall/|title=Sarkodie pulls over 3,000 audience at \"Highest\" Album signing at West Hills Mall|work=globalfmonline.com|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ghkings.com/photos-stars-attended-sarkodies-highest-album-signing/ |title=All The Photos: Stars Who Attended Sarkodie\u2019s \"Highest\" Album Signing |website=GhKings.com |access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!width=\"250\"| Awards ceremony\n!width=\"450\"| Award description(s)\n!width=\"75\" | Results\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n|3 Music Awards\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Album of The Year\n|{{won}} <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydjlive.com/full-list-the-3-music-awards-winners/|title=3 Music Awards |publisher=Ebeneza DonkorLIVE |date= |accessdate=2018-03-24}}</ref>\n|-\n|Ghana Entertainment Awards\n|{{won}} <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydjlive.com/2018-ghana-entertainment-awards-usa-full-list-of-winners/|title=2018 Ghana Entertainment Awards USA {{!}} Full List of Winners |publisher=Ebeneza DonkorLIVE |date= |accessdate=2018-07-02}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track list\n| all_writing     = Sarkodie \n| title1          = Silence (feat. Suli Breaks)\n| writer1         = \n| length1         = 4:07\n| title2          = Overdose (feat. [[Jesse Jagz]])\n| writer2         = \n| length2         = 3:24\n| title3          = [[Come to Me (Sarkodie song)|Come to Me]] (feat. Bobii Lewis)\n| writer3         = \n| length3         = 4:07\n| title4          = Interlude - Highest, Pt. 1\n| writer4         = \n| length4         = 0:35\n| title5          = We No Dey Fear\n| writer5         = \n| length5         = 4:05\n| title6          = Certified (feat. Jayso & Worlasi)\n| writer6         = \n| length6         = 3:29\n| title7          = Love Yourself (feat. [[Moelogo]])\n| writer7         = \n| length7         = 3:00\n| title8          = Interlude - Highest, Pt. 2\n| writer8         = \n| length8         = 0:35\n| title9          = Highest\n| writer9         = \n| length9         = 3:00\n| title10         = Light It Up (feat. [[Big Narstie]] & [[Jayso]])\n| writer10        = \n| length10        = 4:57\n| title11         = Far Away (feat. Korede Bello)\n| writer11        = \n| length11        = 4:36\n| title12         = Your Waist\n| writer12        =\n| length12        = 3:33\n| title13         = Inter