roducer)|Tommy Brown]]\n*[[Noel Zancanella]]\n*[[Hollywood Hot Sauce|Hot Sauce]]\n*[[Cashmere Cat]]\n*[[Lido (musician)|Lido]]\n*[[Darkchild]]\n*[[Ilya Salmanzadeh]]\n*[[Zedd]]\n*[[Key Wane]]\n*[[Pop & Oak]]\n*[[Ali Payami]]\n*[[Peter Svensson]]\n*[[Carolina Liar|Johan Carlsson]]\n*[[Victoria Mon\u00e9t]]\n*[[Carolina Liar|Rickard G\u00f6ransson]]\n*[[Kuk Harrell]]\n*Travis Sayles\n*[[Harmony Samuels]]\n*Jo Blaq\n| prev_title   = [[Christmas Kisses (EP)|Christmas Kisses]]\n| prev_year    = 2013\n| next_title   = [[The Remix (Ariana Grande album)|The Remix]]\n| next_year    = 2015\n| misc         = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Ariana Grande studio albums\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = [[Yours Truly (Ariana Grande album)|Yours Truly]]\n | prev_year  = 2013\n | title      = My Everything\n | year       = 2014\n | next_title = [[Dangerous Woman]]\n | next_year  = 2016\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = My Everything\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Problem (song)|Problem]]\n | single1date = April 28, 2014\n | single2     = [[Break Free (song)|Break Free]]\n | single2date = July 2, 2014\n | single3     = [[Bang Bang (Jessie J, Ariana Grande and Nicki Minaj song)|Bang Bang]]\n | single3date = July 28, 2014\n | single4     = [[Love Me Harder]]\n | single4date = September 30, 2014\n | single5     = [[One Last Time (Ariana Grande song)|One Last Time]]\n | single5date = February 10, 2015\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''My Everything''''' is the second [[studio album]] by American singer [[Ariana Grande]], released on August 25, 2014 by [[Republic Records]]. Grande wanted ''My Everything'' to sound as \"an evolution\" from her debut album, ''[[Yours Truly (Ariana Grande album)|Yours Truly]]'' (2013); it explores more mature themes and music genres. In the album's production, Grande worked with a host of producers and co-writers \u2013 including [[Max Martin]], [[Shellback (record producer)|Shellback]], [[Benny Blanco]], [[Ryan Tedder]], [[Darkchild]], [[Ilya Salmanzadeh]], [[Zedd]], and [[David Guetta]], to name a few. Upon its release, the album debuted atop the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart in the United States, selling 169,000 copies in its first week there. It debuted at number one in Australia and Canada as well, and peaked in the top ten of twenty countries worldwide. As of April 2018, the album has sold 735,000 copies in the United States alone.<ref name=\"us_sales\"/>\n\n''My Everything'' was preceded by the [[lead single]] \"[[Problem (song)|Problem]]\", which features Australian rapper [[Iggy Azalea]]. After its release on April 28, 2014, the single debuted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] singles chart in the US at number three the week ending May 17, selling over 400,000 copies in its first week and eventually peaking at number two. \"[[Break Free (song)|Break Free]]\", featuring German-Russian musician and producer Zedd, was released as the second single on July 2, and peaked at number four on the Hot 100. The fourth single, \"[[Love Me Harder]]\", with Canadian recording artist [[The Weeknd]], was released on September 30, 2014 and eventually peaked at number seven in the US, while final single \"[[One Last Time (Ariana Grande song)|One Last Time]]\" reached number thirteen. At the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]] in 2015, ''My Everything'' was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Grammys 2015: See the Full List of Nominees|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/6363565/grammys-2015-nominations-57th-annual|website=Billboard|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Background and recording==\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = \"It's an album that I want to do a little bit different. I don't want it to sound like an extension of ''[[Yours Truly (Ariana Grande album)|Yours Truly]]''. I want it to sound like an evolution. I want to explore more sounds and experiment a little bit. I have a bunch of ideas I'm very excited about and a lot of stuff cooking.\"\n| source =&nbsp;\u2014 Grande, on the album.<ref name=Extension>{{cite web|last1=Krishnamurthy|first1=Sowmya|title=Q&A: Ariana Grande on 'Yours Truly' and Judging Miley Cyrus|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/q-a-ariana-grande-on-yours-truly-and-judging-miley-cyrus-20130911|website=Rolling Stone|date=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n| bgcolor = #FFFFF0\n| width  = 25%\n| align  = left\n}}\n\nGrande's debut studio album ''[[Yours Truly (Ariana Grande album)|Yours Truly]]'' was released on September 3, 2013, and was met with critical acclaim. Later that month, in an interview with ''Rolling Stone'', Grande stated that she had begun writing and working on her second studio album and had already completed two songs.<ref name=\"Extension\" /> Recording sessions began in October 2013 with Grande working with previous producers from her debut album [[Harmony Samuels]] and Tommy Brown.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ariana Grande Twitter announces she's working on second album in studio|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/3392/20140113/ariana-grande-twitter-announces-shes-working-second-album-studio.htm|journal=Music Times}}</ref><ref name=\"Ridiculous\">{{cite web|last1=Joanne|first1=Dorke|title=Ariana Grande Confirms New Song 'Ridiculous'|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/ariana-grande/news/ariana-grande-confirms-new-song-ridiculous|website=MTV News UK|date=October 13, 2013}}</ref> Grande was initially aiming at releasing the album around February 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande Starts Working On Her Second Album|url=http://www.disneydreaming.com/2013/10/31/ariana-grande-starts-working-on-her-second-album/|publisher=Disneydreaming.com|access-date=June 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203014804/http://www.disneydreaming.com/2013/10/31/ariana-grande-starts-working-on-her-second-album/|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In January 2014, Grande confirmed she had been working with new producers [[Ryan Tedder]], [[Savan Kotecha]], [[Benny Blanco]], [[Key Wane]] and [[Max Martin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Christina|title=Ariana Grande Talks Working With Max Martin For Second Album|url=http://www.idolator.com/7503309/ariana-grande-second-album-producers-max-martin|publisher=SpinMedia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Fox|first=Sarah|title=Ariana Grande back to work in the studio, recording second album|url=http://theslanted.com/2014/01/12960/ariana-grande-back-to-work-in-the-studio-recording-second-album/|publisher=Grimm Media Publications LLC}}</ref><ref name=\"billboard.com\">{{cite web|last1=Lipshutz|first1=Jason|title=Ariana Grande Talks 'Problem' Single & Second Album, Due Out August/September|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6070079/ariana-grande-talks-problem-single-second-album-due-out|website=Billboard|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref> Grande stated in late February that she wanted to name her album after a song she had finished that weekend that is very honest and makes her cry.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grande|first1=Ariana|title=progress update! I think I want to name the album...|url=https://www.facebook.com/arianagrande/posts/10151965028436027?stream_ref=10|website=Facebook|date=February 25, 2014}}{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Carl|title=Ariana Grande Teases Her Second Album: \"It's Very Special and Honest'|url=http://www.sugarscape.com/main-topics/music/1020852/ariana-grande-teases-her-second-album-its-very-special-and-honest|website=Sugar Scape|date=February 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced on March 3, 2014 that Grande would be featured on the fifth single from [[Chris Brown]]'s album ''[[X (Chris Brown album)|X]]'' titled \"Don't Be Gone Too Long\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Wass|first=Mike|title=Ariana Grande's Duet With Chris Brown Is Apparently Called \"Don't Be Gone Too Long\"|url=http://www.idolator.com/7508177/ariana-grande-duet-chris-brown-dont-be-gone-too-long|publisher=SpinMedia}}</ref> The single was originally set for release on March 25, 2014. However, it was postponed due to Brown being sent to jail awaiting trial on assault charges.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|last=Wass|first=Mike|title=Chris Brown And Ariana Grande's Duet \"Don't Be Gone Too Long\" Has Been Postponed|url=http://www.idolator.com/7510240/chris-brown-ariana-grande-duet-postponed|publisher=SpinMedia}}</ref> Grande had announced the song's delay on March 17, 2014 via Twitter stating \"My loves\u2026 so obviously some things have changed recently... So we have to delay the dbgtl countdown, some things are out of our control\".<ref name=\":1\" /> That same night she held a live stream to make up for the single's delay, where she previewed four new songs from her second album.<ref>{{cite web|last=Inocencio|first=Marc|title=Ariana Grande Teases Four New Songs During LiveStream: Listen|url=http://www.ryanseacrest.com/2014/03/24/ariana-grande-teases-four-news-song-during-livestream-listen/|publisher=Ryan Seacrest Productions}}</ref><ref name=Livesteam>{{cite web|last1=Garibaldi|first1=Christina|title=Ariana Grande Teases New Music in Livestream\u2026And Everyone Missed It?|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1724688/ariana-grande-teases-new-music-in-livestreamand-everyone-missed-it/|publisher=MTV|date=March 24, 2014}}</ref> Two days following the announcement, Grande revealed that due to the song's delay, she would be releasing the first single from her upcoming sophomore studio album instead.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grande|first=Ariana|title=now you'll be getting my 1st|url=https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/446445506508898304|publisher=Twitter}}{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Grande confirms Brown single is on hold|url=http://www.covermg.com/grande-confirms-brown-single-is-on-hold/|publisher=Think Agency|access-date=June 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518025642/http://www.covermg.com/grande-confirms-brown-single-is-on-hold/|archive-date=May 18, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> She finished working on the album in late May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande Is Completing Her Sophomore Album This Week|url=http://www.disneydreaming.com/2014/05/23/ariana-grande-is-completing-her-sophomore-album-this-week/|website=Disney Dreaming|date=May 23, 2014|access-date=June 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714130149/http://www.disneydreaming.com/2014/05/23/ariana-grande-is-completing-her-sophomore-album-this-week/|archive-date=July 14, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> On June 28, Grande confirmed the title of the album to be ''My Everything'' and the release date to be August 25, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Peters|first1=Mitchell|title=Ariana Grande Announces Second Album \u2018My Everything,\u2019 Teases \u2018Break Free\u2019 Video|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6141064/ariana-grande-announces-second-album-my-everything-teases-break-free-zedd|website=Billboard|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> The photos for the packaging in the album were taken on May 27, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande Teases \"Problem\" Music Video: It\u2019s Coming Soon!|url=http://www.bopandtigerbeat.com/2014/05/ariana-grande-teases-problem-music-video-its-coming-soon/|website=Tiger Beat|date=May 28, 2014|access-date=June 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101213431/http://www.bopandtigerbeat.com/2014/05/ariana-grande-teases-problem-music-video-its-coming-soon/|archive-date=January 1, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Grande stated that she chose the cover artwork because she felt that \"each song is so strongly themed that I just wanted to have a very simple overall cover. So that within each song we could create more visual themes.\"<ref name=ExclusiveContent>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande Announces Exclusive Concert!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NorphRjDAyc|via=YouTube|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n''My Everything'' is a [[Pop music|pop]]-[[contemporary R&B|R&B]] album.<ref name=\"My Everything \u2013 Billboard Review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6229287/ariana-grande-my-everything-billboard-album-review|title=My Everything \u2013 Billboard Review|access-date= November 6, 2016}}</ref> It revisits the '90's [[retro style|retro]]-[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] style present in Grande's debut album ''[[Yours Truly (Ariana Grande album)|Yours Truly]]'': Annie Zaleski from ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', described the album as a \"slick throwback to melodramatic \u201980s and \u201990s pop.\"<ref name=\"TheAVClub\"/> The album's tracks include [[Electronic dance music|EDM]], [[hip hop]] tunes and piano-driven [[ballad]]s.<ref name=\"My Everything \u2013 Billboard Review\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/stars-ariana-grande-article-1.1912013|title= Ariana Grande's 'My Everything': Album Review|newspaper= Daily News|location=New York|access-date= November 6, 2016}}</ref> The album opens with \"Intro\", in which Grande addresses her fans: \"I'll give you all I have and nothing less, I promise\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ariana-grandes-new-album-my-everything-track-by-track-review__7487/|title=Official Charts 'My Everything\"' Review|access-date=November 6, 2016|publisher=Official Charts}}</ref> The second track is the lead single \"[[Problem (song)|Problem]]\", an uptempo [[dance-pop]] song influenced by R&B,<ref name=\"Huff\">{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/28/ariana-grande-problem_n_5226140.html |title=Ariana Grande Drops New Single 'Problem' Featuring Iggy Azalea |first=Ryan |last=Kristobak |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=April 19, 2014}}; and {{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7516011/ariana-grande-iggy-azalea-problem-review-revue|title=Ariana Grande & Iggy Azalea 'Problem' Review|publisher=Idolator|date=April 28, 2014|access-date= November 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|last1=Wass|first1=Mike| title=Ariana Grande Debuts \"Problem\" With Sexy Radio Disney Music Awards Performance: Watch|url=http://www.idolator.com/7515862/ariana-grande-problem-performance-radio-disney-music-awards|website=Idolator|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref> [[jazz]], [[hip hop]] and [[funk]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|title=Review: Ariana Grande's hot new single 'Problem' is problem-free anthem for the summer [LISTEN]|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/5770/20140428/review-ariana-grandes-hot-new-single-problem-free-anthem-summer.htm|publisher=MusicTimes.com|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Rap-Up]]'' described the track as an \"infectious horn-heavy jam\" that features a \"carefree\" Grande \"declaring her independence\". It includes \"an empowering verse from [[Iggy Azalea]] and a whispering Big Sean on the hook.\"<ref name=\"Rap Up\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/04/27/new-music-ariana-grande-f-iggy-azalea-problem/ |title=New Music: Ariana Grande f/ Iggy Azalea \u2013 'Problem' |publisher=Rap-Up. SpinMedia |date=April 27, 2014 |accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref> \"[[One Last Time (Ariana Grande song)|One Last Time]]\" is a [[dance-pop]] and EDM-light song.<ref name=officialchartscompany>{{cite web|last1=Copsey|first1=Rob|title=Ariana Grande goes it alone on new single 'One Last Time'|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ariana-grandes-new-album-my-everything-track-by-track-review-3046/|publisher=Official Chart Company|date=February 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=popmattersA>{{cite news| last1=Sawdey|first1=Evan|title=Ariana Grande: My Everything &#124; PopMatters|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/185041-ariana-grande-my-everything| accessdate= November 6, 2016| work=[[PopMatters]]|date=August 25, 2014}}</ref> The album continues with \"Why Try\", co-written and co-produced by [[Ryan Tedder]] and [[Benny Blanco]] and features the lyrics \"Now we're screaming just to see who's louder\".<ref name=\"My Everything \u2013 Billboard Review\"/> Some critics expressed an opinion that the song has a similar composition with [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s \"[[XO (song)|XO]]\" (2013; also produced by Tedder).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/ariana-grande-my-everything-20140826|title= Ariana Grande My Everything|publisher=Rob Sheffield \u2013 [[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|access-date= November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe following track is the EDM song [[Break Free (song)|\"Break Free\"]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sherman|first1=Maria|title=Ariana Grande Is Going EDM With Zedd on New Album| url=http://www.fuse.tv/2014/04/ariana-grande-zedd-new-album|website=Fuse|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref> The song combines the EDM and [[Electro (music)|electro]] genres.<ref>{{cite web| title=Listen to Ariana Grande Go EDM with Zedd on 'Break Free'| url=http://radio.com/2014/07/02/ariana-grande-zedd-break-free-listen-edm| publisher=Radio.com| date=July 2, 2014| access-date=November 6, 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903165103/http://radio.com/2014/07/02/ariana-grande-zedd-break-free-listen-edm/| archive-date=September 3, 2017| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"axs.com\">Villa, Lucas. [http://www.axs.com/listen-zedd-helps-ariana-grande-break-free-on-new-dance-track-13742 \"Listen: Zedd helps Ariana Grande 'Break Free' on new dance track\"], ''AXS''. Retrieved July 3, 2014.</ref> In an interview with ''Billboard'', Grande described the song as \"fantastic and super-experimental for [her]\" and stated: \"I never thought I'd do an EDM song, but that was an eye-opening experience, and now all I want to do is dance.\"<ref name=\"billboard.com\"/> The album's first of three ballads, \"Best Mistake\", features [[Big Sean]]. ''Billboard'' described it as \"A moody ballad that grows stickier upon each listen, \"Best Mistake\" carries a tidy collection of impressive production details, the momentary string stabs among them\".<ref name=\"My Everything \u2013 Billboard Review\"/> Musically, it is a [[Minimal music|minimal]] hip-hop piano ballad lament that utilizes instrumentation from strings and a drum machine.<ref name = \"Billboard\"/> It tells a story about a couple trying to \"make up their minds about the future of their relationship, with deep affection buried underneath their problems.\"<ref name = \"Billboard\">{{cite web|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason| date=August 12, 2014|title=Ariana Grande & Big Sean Re-Team For 'Best Mistake': Listen|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6214406/ariana-grande-big-sean-best-mistake|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140902202810/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6214406/ariana-grande-big-sean-best-mistake|archivedate=September 2, 2014|accessdate=September 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Zaleski|first=Annie|date=August 26, 2014| url=http://www.avclub.com/review/ariana-grandes-sweet-sweet-fantasies-are-polished--208534|title=Ariana Grande's sweet, sweet fantasies are polished but disappointing| work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901091610/http://www.avclub.com/review/ariana-grandes-sweet-sweet-fantasies-are-polished--208534|archivedate=September 1, 2014|accessdate=September 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wood|first=Mikael|title=Ariana Grande Dials It Down With Big Sean In 'Best Mistake'|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-listen-ariana-grande-big-sean-best-mistake-20140812-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]]|date=August 12, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901053026/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-listen-ariana-grande-big-sean-best-mistake-20140812-story.html|archivedate=September 1, 2014|accessdate=September 2, 2014}}</ref> \"Be My Baby\" featuring [[Cashmere Cat]] is a \"bouncy R&B jam\".<ref name=\"officialcharts.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ariana-grandes-new-album-my-everything-track-by-track-review__7487/|title= Official Charts 'My Everything\"' Review|access-date= November 6, 2016|publisher= Official Charts}}</ref> The song was compared with [[Mariah Carey]]'s songs.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6229287/ariana-grande-my-everything-billboard-album-review|title=My Everything \u2013 Billboard Review}}</ref> The eighth track, \"Break Your Heart Right Back\", featuring [[Childish Gambino]], is about her boyfriend cheating on her with a man and contains the lyrics \"I know you\u2019re mad 'cause I found out / Want you to feel what I feel right now\". The song interpolates [[Diana Ross]]'s \"[[I'm Coming Out]].\"<ref name=\"officialcharts.com\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n\"[[Love Me Harder]]\", featuring [[The Weeknd]], is a mid-tempo [[synthpop]] and R&B song,<ref>{{cite news|title=New Music: Ariana Grande f/ The Weeknd \u2013 'Love Me Harder'|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/08/20/new-music-ariana-grande-f-the-weeknd-love-me-harder/|accessdate=March 28, 2016| work=[[Rap-Up]]|publisher=Townsquare Music|date=August 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"complex\">{{cite web |last=Ortiz |first=Edwin |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/12/best-songs-2014/ariana-grande-love-me-harder |title=Ariana Grande f/ the Weeknd \"Love Me Harder\" \u2013 The 50 Best Songs of 2014 |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=December 8, 2014 |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-review-ariana-grande-makes-big-things-happen-on-my-everything-20140829-story.html|access-date= November 7, 2016| date= August 29, 2014|title= Review: Ariana Grande makes big things happen on headstrong 'My Everything'}}</ref> which starts small before its \"'throbbing', electro-heavy chorus\",<ref name=\"officialcharts\">{{cite news|last1=Copsey|first1=Rob| title=Ariana Grande's new album My Everything: Track-by-track review|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ariana-grandes-new-album-my-everything-track-by-track-review__7487/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|date=August 17, 2014}}</ref> with a [[guitar riff]],<ref name=\"billboardreview\">{{cite news| last1=Lipshut|first1=Jason|title=Ariana Grande Expands on 'My Everything': Track-By-Track Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6229287/ariana-grande-my-everything-billboard-album-review|accessdate=March 28, 2016|work=Billboard|date=August 25, 2014}}</ref> while \"big vacuum-esque synths zip\" can be heard throughout the track.<ref name=\"popjustice\">{{cite news|last1=Cragg|first1=Michael|title=Ariana Grande's \u2018My Everything\u2019: A first listen review thing|url=http://www.popjustice.com/briefing/guests/ariana-grandes-my-everything-a-first-listen-review-thing/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|work=[[Popjustice]]|date=August 18, 2014}}</ref> Rob Copsey wrote for [[The Official Charts Company]] that the song reminded him of [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] at his most emotional.<ref name=\"officialcharts\"/> Lyrically, the song has Grande demanding romantic satisfaction,<ref name=\"billboardreview\"/> using [[double entendre]]s about [[BDSM]].<ref name=\"latimes\"/> The track \"Just a Little Bit of Your Heart\" is the album's second ballad, co-written by [[Harry Styles]].<ref name=\"My Everything \u2013 Billboard Review\"/><ref name=\"Official Charts Review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ariana-grandes-new-album-my-everything-track-by-track-review__7487/|title= Official Charts Review|access-date= November 6, 2016}}</ref> Official Charts compared the eleventh track, \"Hands on Me\", featuring [[A$AP Ferg]], with [[Rihanna]]'s \"[[Cockiness (Love It)]]\" (2012) and Azalea's \"[[Fancy (Iggy Azalea song)|Fancy]]\" (2014).<ref name=\"Official Charts Review\"/> Jason Lipshutz of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' described \"Hands on Me\" as \"an out-of-left-field banger that removes Grande from her teenybopper phase and finds the 21-year-old discovering her inner Rihanna with lines.\"<ref name=\"My Everything \u2013 Billboard Review\"/> The title track \"My Everything\" concludes the standard edition of the album on a somber note, recalling \"Intro\", and concerns Grande's struggles to regain the solid footing she once had with her partner.<ref name= Billboard/>\n\nThe first bonus track on deluxe edition, \"[[Bang Bang (Jessie J, Ariana Grande and Nicki Minaj song)|Bang Bang]]\", featuring [[Jessie J]] and [[Nicki Minaj]] is an up-tempo, \"soulful\" song that features a \"clap-heavy\" production built over \"big bouncy beats and horn blasts\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/jessie-j/news/jessie-j-ariana-grande-nicki-minaj-finally-unveil-bang-bang |title=Jessie J, Ariana Grande & Nicki Minaj Finally Unveil 'Bang Bang' &#124; MTV UK |publisher=MTV |date=April 29, 2014 |accessdate=July 31, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7528564/jessie-j-ariana-grande-nicki-minaj-bang-bang-listen-to-the-collaboration |title=Jessie J, Ariana Grande and Nicki Minaj's \"Bang Bang\": Listen to the Collaboration &#124; Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on |publisher=Idolator.com |accessdate=July 31, 2014}}</ref> The next track was described by ''Billboard'' as \"short, snappy and sumptuous, 'Only 1' is a light confection that succeeds due to its busy, intricate percussion\".<ref name=\"My Everything \u2013 Billboard Review\"/> The deluxe edition of ''My Everything'' concludes with the track \"You Don't Know Me\".\n\n==Release and promotion==\n[[File:Ariana Grande - The Honeymoon Tour Live Jakarta (4).jpg|right|thumbnail|Grande performing during [[The Honeymoon Tour]] at JIExpo in [[Jakarta]] in 2015.]] \nOn June 28, 2014, Grande announced that her album would be available for pre-order through her website. Those who pre-ordered the album would get exclusive access to Grande's concert stream that will be held on August 24 where she will perform songs from her album live for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grande|first1=Ariana|title=My new album My Everything now available for preorder|url=https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/483068153778286593|website=Twitter|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref> Grande embarked on her first world tour titled [[The Honeymoon Tour]] in support of the album which began in February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lipshutz|first1=Jason|title=Ariana Grande Announces First North American Headlining Tour: See The Full Dates|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6244205/ariana-grande-2015-tour-dates-north-america-honeymoon-tour|website=Billboard|date=September 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the weeks preceding the release of ''My Everything'', several previews of songs from the album were released. On July 7, 2014 Grande posted a teaser of \"[[Best Mistake]]\" onto her Instagram page. The song features rapper [[Big Sean]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee |first1=Christina |title=Ariana Grande Teases 'Best Mistake' Featuring Big Sean: Listen |url=http://www.idolator.com/7525751/ariana-grande-big-sean-best-mistake-preview |website=Idolator |date=July 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808065350/http://www.idolator.com/7525751/ariana-grande-big-sean-best-mistake-preview |archivedate=August 8, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Garibaldi|first1=Christina|title=Ariana Grande Teases \u2018Best Mistake\u2019 Featuring Big Sean: Listen Now|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1862597/ariana-grande-teases-best-mistake-big-sean/|publisher=MTV|date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> On July 27, 2014, a preview of \"Be My Baby\" was filmed at a concert of featured artist, [[Cashmere Cat]], and uploaded to YouTube, by a fan. Grande retweeted a link to the video on her Twitter profile.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cosores|first1=Philip|title=New Ariana Grande Song \u2018Be My Baby\u2019 Previewed at Cashmere Cat DJ Set|url=http://radio.com/2014/07/29/new-ariana-grande-song-be-my-baby-cashmere-cat-preview/|website=Radio.com|date=July 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lynch|first1=Joe|title=Hear Ariana Grande & Cashmere Cat's Surprise Track 'Be My Baby'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6204322/ariana-grande-cashmere-cat-be-my-baby|website=Billboard|date=July 31, 2014}}</ref> She then retweeted a second snippet on August 4.<ref>{{cite web|author=ArianaScoop |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OTfiVnDiLKo |title=(FUL/NEW SNIPPET) Ariana Grande \u2013 Be My Baby ft Cashmere Cat |via=YouTube |date=August 4, 2014 |accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/496515962024103936 |title=Twitter / ArianaGrande: dat audio tho :'( \u00e2\u20ac\u0153@AGrandePR: |publisher=Twitter |date=August 4, 2014 |accessdate=August 20, 2014}}{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref> Twenty days before the album's release, Grande released a preview of \"[[Love Me Harder]]\", which features Canadian recording artist [[The Weeknd]], onto her Instagram profile.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hyndman|first1=Jessica|title=Listen to a Snippet Of Ariana Grande's Collab with the Weeknd On \u2018Love Me Harder\u2019|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1888922/ariana-grande-weeknd-love-me-harder/|publisher=MTV|accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> On August 20, four songs from the album, \"Why Try\", \"Be My Baby\", \"Love Me Harder\", and \"Just a Little Bit of Your Heart\", were released courtesy of [[MTV]].<ref>{{cite web |work=Billboard|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6221962/ariana-grande-harry-styles-new-songs-my-everything|title=Ariana Grande Premieres 4 New Songs, Including Harry Styles-Penned Ballad|first=Erin|last=Strecker|accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, Grande opened the [[2014 MTV Video Music Awards]] with \"[[Break Free (song)|Break Free]]\" and then later appeared to perform \"[[Bang Bang (Jessie J, Ariana Grande and Nicki Minaj song)|Bang Bang]]\" with [[Jessie J]] and [[Nicki Minaj]]. Following her performance on the show, ''My Everything'' was released worldwide on August 25, 2014. During the week of its release, commercials aired on television to promote ''My Everything'' as well as the [[Beats Pill]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Farley|first1=Christopher John|title=Triple-Platform Push for Ariana Grande's Album|url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/triple-platform-push-for-ariana-grandes-album-1408317171|website=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> On August 29, Grande performed \"[[Problem (song)|Problem]]\", \"Break Free\", \"Bang Bang\", and \"Break Your Heart Right Back\" on ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|The Today Show]]''. In addition to performing, Grande was also interviewed, forecasted to weather and brought her grandmother for an interview of her own.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande brings her 'Everything' to mob of fans on TODAY plaza|url=http://www.today.com/toyotaconcertseries/ariana-grande-brings-big-talent-crowds-today-plaza-1D80115170|website=Today|date=August 29, 2014}}</ref> On September 5, Grande performed the title track from ''My Everything'' during the [[Stand Up to Cancer]] television program in dedication to her grandfather, who had died from cancer earlier that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celeb-Packed \u2018Stand Up To Cancer\u2019 Telecast Returns Friday Night|url=http://miami.cbslocal.com/2014/09/05/stand-up-to-cancer-telecast-to-return-sept-5-2/|website=CBS Local|date=September 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Singles==\nGrande premiered her first single \"[[Problem (song)|Problem]]\", which features Australian rapper [[Iggy Azalea]], at the [[2014 Radio Disney Music Awards]] and released it for digital download later that night on April 28, 2014. The song debuted at number three on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and sold 438,000 units in its first week making it the fifth largest debut by a woman in history.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=John Legend's 'All Of Me' Tops Hot 100, Ariana Grande Debuts at No. 3|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6077635/hot-100-john-legend-all-of-me-ariana-grande-iggy-azalea|website=Billboard}}</ref> The single later peaked at number two on the Hot 100, holding that position for five non-consecutive weeks.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Iggy Azalea Tops Hot 100 With 'Fancy,' Matches Beatles' History Mark|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6099390/iggy-azalea-tops-hot-100-fancy-matches-beatles|date=May 28, 2014}}</ref> The single has sold 3.<!--pure sales per Billboard citation-->7&nbsp;million copies in the US and has been certified sextuple [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) in March 2016.\n\nThe second single, \"[[Break Free (song)|Break Free]]\", features electronic music producer [[Zedd (musician)|Zedd]] and was released on July 2, 2014. The song debuted at number 15 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 with 161,000 downloads sold in its first week.<ref>Trust, Gary. [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6150450/hot-100-iggy-azalea-fancy-maroon-5-maps \"Iggy Azalea Tops Hot 100 For Seventh Week, Maroon 5's 'Maps' Finds Top 10\"], ''Billboard''. Retrieved July 9, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande's Break Free Debuts Strong on Hot 100 and Digital Charts|url=http://singersroom.com/content/2014-07-10/Ariana-Grandes-Break-Free-Debuts-Strong-on-Hot-100-and-Digital-Charts/|website=Singers Room|date=July 10, 2014}}</ref> After the release of the song's music video, \"Break Free\" soared on the Hot 100 from number 18 to number four,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Ariana Grande, Iggy Azalea Triple Up in Hot 100's Top 10, MAGIC! Still No. 1|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6221978/hot-100-ariana-grande-iggy-azalea-top-10-magic|website=Billboard|accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref> while Grande's other singles, \"[[Bang Bang (Jessie J, Ariana Grande, and Nicki Minaj song)|Bang Bang]]\" and \"[[Problem (song)|Problem]]\" were also in the top ten that week, at numbers ten and seven respectively. With three songs in the top ten, Ariana Grande became the second female lead artist to have three singles in the top ten since [[Adele]] in 2012. It also reached number one on the ''Billboard'' [[Dance/Electronic Digital Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2014-08-16/dance-electronic-digital-songs|title=Dance/Electronic Digital Songs|date=August 16, 2014|work=Billboard|accessdate=September 23, 2014}}</ref> \"Break Free\" has sold 1.9&nbsp;million copies as of April 2018, and is certified triple platinum by the RIAA.<ref name=\"RIAAcert\">{{cite web | url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Ariana+Grande#search_section | title=Gold & Platinum: Ariana Grande | publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] | accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Bang Bang (Jessie J, Ariana Grande and Nicki Minaj song)|Bang Bang]]\" by [[Jessie J]], Ariana Grande, and [[Nicki Minaj]], was first sent to [[hot adult contemporary]] radios on July 28, 2014, through [[Republic Records]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/hot-modern-ac/future-releases |title=Hot/Modern/AC Future Releases |publisher=All Access. All Access Music Group |accessdate=April 30, 2017 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RLTLZ3sS?url=http://www.allaccess.com/hot-modern-ac/future-releases |archivedate=July 26, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the label that houses all three artists, being released as a digital download on July 29, 2014, through [[Lava Records|Lava]] and Republic, serving as a joint single.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.company.co.uk/magazine-hq/jessie-j-ariana-grande-nicki-minaj-new-song-bang-bang|title = Jessie J, Ariana Grande and Nicki Minaj to Release a Joint Single!|date = July 2, 2014|accessdate = July 8, 2014|website = Company|last = Lee|first = Earnest}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/nicki-minaj-ariana-grande-jessie-j-at-work-on-joint-single-bang-bang-1.8646528|title = Nicki Minaj, Ariana Grande, Jessie J at work on joint single 'Bang Bang'|date = July 2, 2014|accessdate = July 8, 2014|website = Newsday|publisher = 2014 Newsday|last = Deals|first = Travis}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.mashable.com/2014/07/01/jessie-j-ariana-grande-nicki-minaj-bang-bang-song/|title = Lady Marmalade' Part 2? Ariana Grande, Nicki Minaj, Jessie J Team Up|date = July 1, 2014|accessdate = July 8, 2014|website = Mashable|publisher = Mashable|last = Hernandez|first = Brian}}</ref> It serves as the lead single from Jessie J's album [[Sweet Talker (Jessie J album)|''Sweet Talker'']], and the third single from ''My Everything''.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6546185/five-hits-one-album-the-strategy-behind-ariana-grandes-singles?source=gravity|title = Five Hits, One Album: The Strategy Behind Ariana Grande's Singles From 'My Everything'|date = April 28, 2015|accessdate = April 29, 2015|website = Billboard|last = Crow|first = Jones}}</ref> The song debuted at number six, and peaked at number three on the Hot 100, while debuting atop the [[UK Singles Chart]]. As of November 2017, \"Bang Bang\" was certified sextuple platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]],<ref>{{cite certification | region=United States | artist=Jessie J, Ariana Grande and Nicki Minaj | title=Bang Bang | type=single | accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> and has sold 3.4&nbsp;million copies in the US since its release.<ref name=\"us_sales\"/>\n\nThe fourth single, \"[[Love Me Harder]]\", which features Canadian [[PBR&B]] artist [[The Weeknd]], was released to [[rhythmic crossover]] radio on September 30, 2014. It debuted at number 79, and later peaked at number seven on the Hot 100, making Grande the artist with the most top-ten singles in 2014. It also became The Weeknd's first top ten entry in the United States.<ref name=\"Love Me Harder radio\">{{cite web|title=Top 40 Rhythmic Future Releases|url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|publisher= All Access Music Group|accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref> As of April 2018, the song had sold 1.7&nbsp;million copies in the United States and has been certified triple platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref name=\"us_sales\"/>\n\n\"[[One Last Time (Ariana Grande song)|One Last Time]]\" was released to [[rhythmic crossover]] and [[contemporary hit radio]] stations on February 10, 2015, as the fifth and final single.<ref name=\"TOP40\">{{cite web |url=http://www.republicplaybook.com/track/ariana-grande-one-last-time/ |title=Top 40 {{!}} Ariana Grande \"One Last Time\" {{!}} Republic Playbook|publisher=[[Republic Records]] |accessdate=January 27, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127153427/http://www.republicplaybook.com/track/ariana-grande-one-last-time/ |archivedate=January 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.republicplaybook.com/track/ariana-grande-one-last-time-2/ |title=Rhythm {{!}} Ariana Grande \"One Last Time\" {{!}} Republic Playbook |publisher=[[Republic Records]] |accessdate=January 27, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202174504/http://www.republicplaybook.com/track/ariana-grande-one-last-time-2/ |archivedate=February 2, 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\"Apple\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/one-last-time-single/id910708842 |title=One Last Time \u2013 Single by Ariana Grande |publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=August 22, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SA5rx2F5?url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/one-last-time-single/id910708842 |archivedate=August 28, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It debuted at number 80 on the Hot 100 and peaked at number 13, becoming the only single from the album to not reach the top ten.<ref name=\"Apple\"/> As of April 2018, \"One Last Time\" has sold 881,000 digital units in the US,<ref name=\"us_sales\"/> and is certified Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Ariana+Grande#search_section | title=Gold & Platinum: Ariana Grande | publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] | accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Promotional singles===\n\"[[Best Mistake]]\" featuring [[Big Sean]] was released on August 12, 2014 as a promotional single to those who preorder the album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grande|first1=Ariana|title=To everybody who has preordered My Everything....|url=https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/497163417250054144|website=Twitter|accessdate=August 7, 2014}}{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hyndman|first1=Jessica|title=Ariana Grande And Big Sean Slow It Down On \u2018Best Mistake\u2019|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1895856/ariana-grande-best-mistake-big-sean/|publisher=MTV|accessdate=August 12, 2014}}</ref> Shortly after its release, \"Best Mistake\" reached No. 1 on the [[Billboard Twitter Real-Time|''Billboard'' Twitter Real-Time]] and the iTunes singles chart.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grande|first1=Ariana|title=iTunes update|url=http://instagram.com/p/roPaqVyWZq/?modal=true|website=Instagram|date=August 13, 2014}}</ref> It sold 104,000 units in its first week landing at number six on the [[Digital Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cantor|first1=Brian|title=Ariana Grande's \"Best Mistake\" Sales Reach 104k|url=http://headlineplanet.com/home/2014/08/20/ariana-grandes-best-mistake-sales-reach-104k/|website=Headline Planet|accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Caulfield|first1=Keith|title=Billboard 200: Did 'Guardians of the Galaxy' Soundtrack Stay at No. 1?|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6221958/guardians-of-the-galaxy-soundtrack-billboard-200-chart|website=Billboard|accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref> It also peaked at number 49 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 6.3/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web|title=My Everything by Ariana Grande reviews {{!}} Any Decent Music|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/6642/Ariana-Grande-My-Everything.aspx|website=www.anydecentmusic.com|accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| MC = 64/100<ref name=\"metacritic.com\"/>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=AllMusic/>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = C+<ref name=TheAVClub/>\n| rev3 = ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n| rev3Score = 81/100<ref name=BillboardReview/>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = B\u2013<ref name=EntertainmentWeekly/>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=TheGuardian/>\n| rev6 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=LosAngelesTimes/>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Observer]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=TheObserver/>\n| rev9 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev9Score = 7.7/10<ref name=Pitchfork/>\n| rev10 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=RollingStone/>\n}}\n\nOn [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[weighted mean|weighted average]] score out of 100 to ratings and reviews from mainstream critics, ''My Everything'' received an average of 64, based on 19 reviews, which the cite defines as \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"metacritic.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/my-everything/ariana-grande/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for My Everything|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref> Rob Sheffield, writing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', says, \"''My Everything'' proves, she's already a major force\" on a release showing how Grande is growing up because \"It's a confident, intelligent, brazen pop statement, mixing bubblegum diva vocals with EDM break-beats.\"<ref name=RollingStone>{{cite journal|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|title=Ariana Grande's New Album: My Everything|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/ariana-grande-my-everything-20140826|journal=Rolling Stone|volume=August 28, 2014|issue=1216|pages=59\u201360|issn=0035-791X|accessdate=August 23, 2014}}</ref> Adam Markovitz says for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' how \"Grande has picked a set of songs so lyrically bland, sonically inoffensive, and artistically empty that they produce a zero-impact experience\u2014musical vanilla fro-yo poured directly into your ears.\"<ref name=EntertainmentWeekly>{{cite web|last1=Markovitz|first1=Adam|title=My Everything Review|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20847052,00.html |work=Entertainment Weekly|date=August 25, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2014}}</ref> Markovitz states, \"It's by no means painful; there are even moments of fun, including the thigh-high-boot swagger of summer smashes 'Problem' and 'Bang Bang,' both of which borrow their strut from coheadliners Iggy Azalea and Jessie J with Nicki Minaj, respectively.\"<ref name=EntertainmentWeekly/> Mikael Wood, writing on behalf of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', finds Grande in impressive form because she is \"deeply cheerful yet with guns blazing, an innocent newcomer no more.\"<ref name=LosAngelesTimes>{{cite web|last=Wood|first=Mikael|title=Review: Ariana Grande makes big things happen on 'My Everything' |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-review-ariana-grande-makes-big-things-happen-on-my-everything-20140829-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 29, 2014|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nElysa Gardner, on behalf of ''[[USA Today]]'', writes that Grande \"digs into ballads and more emotionally earnest fare\" simultaneously, doing so with a \"girlish playfulness... and a sense of growing confidence\", and she is \"Blending sugar and spice\" together to create a pleasing concoction to satisfy the varying palates of her supporters.\"<ref name=USAToday>{{cite web|last1=Gardner|first1=Elysa|title=Ariana's 'My Everything' is all things to all fans|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/08/25/ariana-grande-my-everything-review-listen-up/14547907/|newspaper=USA Today|date=August 25, 2014|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] says for [[AllMusic]] that \"Grande doesn't embody the songs the way an old-fashioned diva would, but she functions as a likeable pop ringleader, stepping aside when the track calls for it and then unleashing a full-throated wail when it's her time to shine.\"<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/my-everything-mw0002698499|title=''My Everything'' \u2013 Ariana Grande &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|publisher=AllMusic|date=August 25, 2014|accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref> Jason Lipshutz from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' writes that the album \"turned Grande into a dance artist, pop artist, and soul artist\" with a more uniformed and more mature sound.<ref name=BillboardReview>{{cite web|last1=Lipshutz|first1=Jason|title=Ariana Grande Expands on 'My Everything': Track-By-Track Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6229287/ariana-grande-my-everything-billboard-album-review|website=Billboard|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref> [[Gary Graff]] says on behalf of ''[[The Oakland Press]]'' that it is \"a solid step forward for Grande, which makes 'there's more to see' an intriguing promise rather than a threat.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Graff|first=Gary|authorlink=Gary Graff|title=Listening Room: Ariana Grande shows growth on sophomore album|url=http://www.theoaklandpress.com/arts-and-entertainment/20140825/listening-room-ariana-grande-shows-growth-on-sophomore-album|newspaper=The Oakland Press|date=August 22, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2014}}</ref> In a 7.7 out of ten review for ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', Meaghan Garvey explains how it \"feels like Grande's arrival as a true pop fixture, not just a charming novelty... and while the best songs here may not be timeless, they certainly feel right for right now.\"<ref name=Pitchfork>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19765-ariana-grande-my-everything/ |title=Ariana Grande: My Everything &#124; Album Reviews |last=Garvey |first=Meaghan |website=Pitchfork |date=August 29, 2014 |accessdate=August 30, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830043900/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19765-ariana-grande-my-everything/ |archivedate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> The album was placed at number eleven on [[Digital Spy]]{{'}}s Best Albums of 2014 list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/feature/a614406/what-is-digital-spys-album-of-the-year-2014-we-reveal-our-top-15.html#~oXNcxv6hrDpwJk|title=Digital Spy's Top Albums Of 2014|author=DigitalSpy|date=December 6, 2014|work=DigitalSpy|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref> Jessica Goodman and Ryan Kistobak of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' included the album on their list of 2014's best releases, commenting that the album makes sure \"Grande's sheer talent did not go unnoticed\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Goodman; Kristobak |first=Jessica; Ryan |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/15/best-albums-2014_n_6326402.html |title=The 23 Best Albums of 2014 |work=HuffPost |date=December 15, 2014 |accessdate=December 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a more mixed review, Jim Farber from the ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' writes that Grande's \"sexed-up\" vocals and range are shown off but the \"constant jerking back and forth between styles interrupts any sense of flow.\"<ref name=NYDN>{{cite web|last1=Farber|first1=Jim|title=Ariana Grande's \u2018My Everything\u2019: Album review|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/stars-ariana-grande-article-1.1912013|website=New York Daily Times|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> Caroline Sullivan from ''[[The Guardian]]'' praises Grande's vocals but feels that the songs are indistinct and have a \"facelessness\" to them.<ref name=TheGuardian>{{cite web|last1=Sullivan|first1=Caroline|title=Ariana Grande: My Everything review \u2013 faceless, generic bangerdom|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/aug/21/ariana-grande-my-everything-review|website=The Guardian|date=August 21, 2014}}</ref> Annie Zaleski writes for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' how it \"is so well-constructed and designed to succeed, it rarely loosens up enough to let any depth of character (or real surprises) surface\", yet it \"further establishes Grande as a consummate performer and vocal interpreter.\"<ref name=TheAVClub>{{cite web|last1=Zaleski |first1=Annie |title=Ariana Grande's sweet, sweet fantasies are polished but disappointing |url=http://www.avclub.com/review/ariana-grandes-sweet-sweet-fantasies-are-polished--208534 |newspaper=The A.V. Club |date=August 26, 2014 |accessdate=August 30, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901091610/http://www.avclub.com/review/ariana-grandes-sweet-sweet-fantasies-are-polished--208534 |archivedate=September 1, 2014}}</ref> [[Kitty Empire]] from ''[[The Observer]]'' notes that Grande's vocal ability is showcased but that the songs lack personality.<ref name=\"TheObserver\">{{cite web|last=Empire|first=Kitty|title=Ariana Grande: My Everything review \u2013 every so often a little shard of personality pierces the sheen|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/aug/24/my-everything-ariana-grande-review-slick-expensive-album|website=The Observer|date=August 23, 2014}}</ref> Evan Sawdey, writing for ''[[PopMatters]]'', commented that Grande mimicks other artists, leaving her distinguished voice with only the support of hollow lyricism.<ref name=popmattersB>{{cite magazine|last=Sawdey|first=Evan|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/185041-ariana-grande-my-everything/|title=Ariana Grande: My Everything|magazine=PopMatters|date=August 25, 2014|accessdate=August 25, 2014}} {{rating|4|10|full=Disc Plain yellow dark.svg|half=AwesomeTemplate.svg|empty=Plain Disc 20% grey.svg|rating=disc}}</ref> In agreement, Will Robinson rated the album a 2.5 out of five for [[Sputnikmusic]], saying it \"ends up ringing hollow\".<ref name=Sputnik>{{cite web|last=Robinson|first=Will|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/63980/Ariana-Grande-My-Everything/|title=Review: Ariana Grande \u2013 My Everything|website=Sputnikmusic|date=August 26, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2014}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' magazine, Adelle Platon was positive towards the album's sound and compared Grande's vocals to those of Mariah Carey and Christina Aguilera.<ref name=VIBE>{{cite web|last=Platon |first=Adelle|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/ariana-grande-my-everything-review|title=Review: Ariana Grande \u2013 My Everything|publisher=VIBE Magazine|date=August 26, 2014|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> Andrew Chan, writing on behalf of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'', stated that Grande \"emphasizes the sheer fun of singing over any sense of emotional urgency\", yet \"What her voice lacks in depth, texture, and variety will probably take time to acquire.\"<ref name=SlantMagazine>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/ariana-grande-my-everything |title=Ariana Grande: My Everything &#124; Album Review |last=Chan |first=Andrew |work=Slant Magazine |date=August 24, 2014 |accessdate=September 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140902203537/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/ariana-grande-my-everything |archivedate=September 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMore than three years after the album's release, Grande's graceful, yet precarious, kneeling pose on a stool for the album's cover suddenly became a viral subject on Twitter, spawning a humorous consfdiracy theory, memes, a \"challenge\" taken up by many to try to recreate the pose, and international press coverage.<ref>Stubblebine, Allison. [http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8005599/ariana-grande-my-everything-stool-meme \"Ariana Grande's Gravity-Defying ''My Everything'' Cover Spawns Best New Conspiracy\"], ''Billboard'', October 17, 2017; Schwartz, Dana. [http://ew.com/music/2017/10/17/ariana-grande-stool-challenge-video \"We tried the Ariana Grande Stool Challenge and it wasn't a complete disaster\"], ''Entertainment Weekly'', October 17, 2017; Bennett, Willa. [http://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/a13029673/people-are-trying-to-replicate-ariana-grandes-my-everything-pose \"People Are Trying to Replicate Ariana Grande's ''My Everything'' Pose\"], ''Seventeen'', October 16, 2017; and Whipple, Tom. [https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/copycat-fans-unsettled-by-ariana-grande-s-pose-for-album-my-everything-nx5b7bg6k \"Copycat fans unsettled by Ariana Grande\u2019s pose for album ''My Everything''\"], ''[[The Times]]'', October 20, 2017</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Year\n! scope=\"row\"| Award\n! scope=\"row\"| Category\n! scope=\"row\"| Result\n! scope=\"row\"| Ref.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\"| 2015\n| [[Grammy Awards]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n| align=\"center\" |<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Grammys 2015: And the Winners Are ...|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/grammys-2015/6465551/grammys-2015-winners-57th-annual|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=July 9, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Japan Gold Disc Award]]s\n|Best 3 Albums (International)\n|{{won}}\n|align=\"center\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aramajapan.com/news/the-japan-gold-disc-award-2015-winners-announced/17222/|title=The Japan Gold Disc Award 2015 Winners Announced|last=Ronald|date=March 4, 2015|website=ARAMA! JAPAN|access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[People's Choice Awards]]\n|[[People's Choice Awards#Categories#Music|Favorite Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n| align=\"center\" |<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/|title= People's Choice Awards 2015 NOMINEES & WINNERS|publisher=[[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice]]|accessdate=July 9, 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Commercial performance==\nOn August 27, ''Billboard'' reported that ''My Everything'' would sell over 160,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|title=Ariana Grande Aiming for Second No. 1 Album|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6229467/ariana-grande-my-everything-no-1|website=Billboard|date=August 27, 2014|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> ''My Everything'' officially debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and sold 169,000 copies in its first week.<ref name=\"BillboardNo.1\">{{cite web|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|title=Ariana Grande Nabs Second No. 1 Album in Less Than A Year|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6236678/ariana-grande-no-1-album-brad-paisley-kem|website=Billboard|date=September 2, 2014|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> By doing so, Grande attained her second consecutive number-one album in the country, becoming the first female artist to have her first two albums debut at number one since Scottish singer [[Susan Boyle]] did it with ''[[I Dreamed a Dream (album)|I Dreamed a Dream]]'' (2009) and ''[[The Gift (Susan Boyle album)|The Gift]]'' (2010).<ref name=\"BillboardNo.1\"/> The album has sold 735,000 copies in the United States as of April 2018.<ref name=\"us_sales\">{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8363518/ariana-grande-career-album-song-sales-ask-billboard|title=Ask Billboard: Ariana Grande's Career Album & Song Sales|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=April 22, 2018|accessdate=April 22, 2018}}</ref> In March 2016, the RIAA certified the album double platinum, for combined album sales, on-demand audio, video streams, track sales equivalent of two million album-equivalent units. In Japan, ''My Everything'' remained atop the [[iTunes Store]] chart for nine weeks, thus earning Grande the longest at number one in 2014, breaking the previous record held by ''[[Frozen (soundtrack)|Frozen: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u5b9f\u529b\u6d3e\u6b4c\u59eb\u30a2\u30ea\u30a2\u30ca\u30fb\u30b0\u30e9\u30f3\u30c7\u3001\u9042\u306b\u30a2\u30ca\u96ea\u8d8a\u3048\uff01|url=http://www.universal-music.co.jp/ariana-grande/news/2014/10/27|website=Billboard|date=October 27, 2014|accessdate=December 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, ''My Everything'' was ranked as the 17th most popular album of the year on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2015/top-billboard-200-albums|title=Top Billboard 200 Albums \u2013 Year-End 2015|work=Billboard|accessdate=December 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 40:34\n| headline = ''My Everything'' {{nobold|\u2013 Standard edition}}<ref>{{cite web|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 My Everything by Ariana Grande|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/my-everything/id894328871|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (NZ). [[Apple Inc.]]|accessdate=July 1, 2014}}</ref>\n| title1 = Intro\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Tommy Brown (record producer)|Tommy Brown]]|[[Victoria Mon\u00e9t]]|[[Ariana Grande]]}}\n| extra1 = Brown\n| length1 = 1:20\n| title2 = [[Problem (song)|Problem]]\n| note2 = featuring [[Iggy Azalea]]\n| writer2 = {{hlist|[[Ilya Salmanzadeh]]|[[Max Martin]]|[[Savan Kotecha]]|Azalea|Grande<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\">Greene, Andy (May 22, 2014)|[[Ariana Grande]] [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/how-ariana-grande-and-max-martin-made-problem-the-song-of-the-summer-20140522 \"How Ariana Grande and Max Martin Made 'Problem' the Song of the Summer\"]. ''[[Rolling Stone]]''. Retrieved November 23, 2015.</ref><!-- Per the album's booklet, she's also listed as a songwriter -->}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|Martin|Ilya|[[Shellback (record producer)|Shellback]]|[[Carolina Liar|Peter Carlsson]]{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length2 = 3:13\n| title3 = [[One Last Time (Ariana Grande song)|One Last Time]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|[[David Guetta]]|Kotecha|[[Giorgio Tuinfort]]|[[Rami Yacoub]]|[[Carl Falk]]}}\n| extra3 = {{hlist||Falk|[[Rami Yacoub|Rami]]|Ilya{{ref|a|[a]}}{{ref|b|[b]}}|Tuinfort{{ref|b|[b]}}|Kotecha{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length3 = 3:17\n| title4 = Why Try\n| writer4 = {{hlist|[[Benny Blanco|Benjamin Levin]]|[[Ryan Tedder]]|[[Ammar Malik]]|[[Noel Zancanella]]}}\n| extra4 = {{hlist|Tedder|[[Benny Blanco]]|Zancanella}}\n| length4 = 3:31\n| title5 = [[Break Free (song)|Break Free]]\n| note5 = featuring [[Zedd]]\n| writer5 = {{hlist|[[Zedd|Anton Zaslavski]]|Martin|Kotecha}}\n| extra5 = {{hlist|Zedd|Martin}}\n| length5 = 3:34\n| title6 = [[Best Mistake]]\n| note6 = featuring [[Big Sean]]\n| writer6 = {{hlist|[[Big Sean|Sean Anderson]]|[[Key Wane|Dwane Weir]]|Grande}}\n| extra6 = {{hlist|[[Key Wane]]|Sauce{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length6 = 3:52\n| title7 = Be My Baby\n| note7 = featuring [[Cashmere Cat]]\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Levin|[[Cashmere Cat|Magnus August H\u00f8iberg]]|[[Rock City (duo)|Theron Thomas]]|[[Rock City (duo)|Timothy Thomas]]|[[Lido (musician)|Peder Losneg\u00e5rd]]}}\n| extra7 = {{hlist|Blanco|Cashmere Cat|[[Lido (musician)|Lido]]}}\n| length7 = 3:37\n| title8 = Break Your Heart Right Back\n| note8 = featuring [[Donald Glover|Childish Gambino]]\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Kirby Dockery|[[Pop Wansel|Andrew \"Pop\" Wansel]]|[[Oak Felder|Warren \"Oak\" Felder]]|[[Donald Glover]]|[[Bernard Edwards]]|[[Nile Rodgers]]|[[Stevie J|Steven Jordan]]|[[The Notorious B.I.G.|Christopher Wallace]]|[[Sean Combs]]|[[Mase|Mason Betha]]}}\n| extra8 = [[Pop & Oak]]\n| length8 = 4:13\n| title9 = [[Love Me Harder]]\n| note9 = with [[The Weeknd]]\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Martin|Kotecha|[[Peter Svensson]]|[[Ali Payami]]|[[The Weeknd|Abel Tesfaye]]|[[Belly (rapper)|Ahmad Balsh